We can see that as $\sigma$ increases from 0.01 to 1 our intercept $b$ decreases, reaching a minimum at $\sigma = 1$; then increases slightly for $\sigma =2$. The intercept of the hyperplane represents the bias of the linear model and determiens the location of the decision boundary with respect to the origin of the feature space. The intercepts are negative which means that hyperplane is shifted towards the negative side of the decision boundary and the model is more likely to identify new points as negative. Since the kernel coefficent determines the importance of a data point on the decsion boundary this can lead to overfitting. Increasing the magnitude of the intercept can lead to a wider margin which reduces the chances of overfitting. Therefoe it is ideal to tune both parameters to build a good model.

2.2.5¶

Now that we have implemented our kernelised SVM classifier, naturally we would like to evaluate the performance which we will do by calculating the accuracy, precision and F-score for each value of $\sigma$. We will first implement a function for the accuracy of our classifier.

In [41]:
def svm_kernel_accuracy(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, lambd, sigma):
    """
    Computes accuracy of kernelised SVM
    
    Args:
        X_train: array of training input
        y_train: vector of training output
        X_test: array of test input
        y_test: vector of test input
        lambd: float, hyper-parameter
        sigma: float, kernel coefficient
        
    Returns:
        Accuracy of kernelised SVM
    """
    # compute kernel matrix from X_train
    k_train = kernel_matrix(X_train, X_train, sigma)
    # obtain weights and intercepts from kernel matrix and y_train
    u, b = sgd_kernel(k_train, y_train, lambd)
    
    # compute new kernel matrix from X_test and X_train
    k_test = kernel_matrix(X_test, X_train, sigma)
    # form prediction from new kernel matrix, weights and intercept
    y_preds = np.sign(k_test @ u + b)
    
    return np.mean(y_preds == y_test)

Next we will create a function to calculate the precision for our kernelised SVM.

In [42]:
def svm_kernel_precision(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, lambd, sigma):
    """
    Computes precision of kernelised SVM
    
    Args:
        X_train: array of training input
        y_train: vector of training output
        X_test: array of test input
        y_test: vector of test input
        lambd: float, hyper-parameter
        sigma: float, kernel coefficient
        
    Returns:
        Precision of kernelised SVM
    """
    # compute kernel matrix from X_train
    k_train = kernel_matrix(X_train, X_train, sigma)
    # obtain weights and intercepts from kernel matrix and y_train
    u, b = sgd_kernel(k_train, y_train, lambd)
    # compute new kernel matrix from X_test and X_train
    k_test = kernel_matrix(X_test, X_train, sigma)
    # form prediction from new kernel matrix, weights and intercept
    y_pred = np.sign(k_test @ u + b)
    
    # create copies to prevent over-writing 
    y_test_copy = y_test.copy()
    y_pred_copy = y_pred.copy()
    
    # change values of -1 to 0 for np.sum
    y_test_copy[y_test_copy == -1] = 0
    y_pred_copy[y_pred_copy == -1] = 0
    
    y_test_copy = y_test_copy.astype(int)
    y_pred_copy = y_pred_copy.astype(int)
    
    # compute number of true positives and false positives
    tp = np.sum(y_test_copy & y_pred_copy)
    fp = np.sum((~y_test_copy) & y_pred_copy)
    
    return tp/(tp+fp)

Lastly, we will create a function to compute the F-score of our model.

In [43]:
def svm_kernel_fscore(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, lambd, sigma):
    """
    Computes F-score of kernelised SVM
    
    Args:
        X_train: array of training input
        y_train: vector of training output
        X_test: array of test input
        y_test: vector of test input
        lambd: float, hyper-parameter
        sigma: float, kernel coefficient
        
    Returns:
        F-score of kernelised SVM
    """
    # compute kernel matrix from X_train
    k_train = kernel_matrix(X_train, X_train, sigma)
    # obtain weights and intercepts from kernel matrix and y_train
    u, b = sgd_kernel(k_train, y_train, lambd)
    # compute new kernel matrix from X_test and X_train
    k_test = kernel_matrix(X_test, X_train, sigma)
    # form prediction from new kernel matrix, weights and intercept
    y_pred = np.sign(k_test @ u + b)
    
    # create copies to prevent over-writing 
    y_test_copy = y_test.copy()
    y_pred_copy = y_pred.copy()
    
    # change values of -1 to 0 for np.sum
    y_test_copy[y_test_copy == -1] = 0
    y_pred_copy[y_pred_copy == -1] = 0
    
    y_test_copy = y_test_copy.astype(int)
    y_pred_copy = y_pred_copy.astype(int)
    
    # compute number of true positives, false positives and false negatives
    tp = np.sum(y_test_copy & y_pred_copy)
    fp = np.sum((~y_test_copy) & y_pred_copy)
    fn = np.sum(y_test_copy & (~y_pred_copy))
    
    return tp/(tp + 0.5*(fp + fn))
